{
  "doc_id": "40613",
  "text": "Besides the evidence showing that inhibition of RAS activity may improve insulin sensitivity, several studies also provide direct evidence implicating over-activation of the RAS in the aetiology of insulin resistance. Chronic angiotensin II infusion causes insulin resistance in rats [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] while the TG(mREN2)27 rat which suffers from chronic systemic RAS over-activation develops muscle and systemic insulin resistance [CITATION_3] . The RAS induced insulin resistance in these animals is improved by renin inhibition or angiotensin receptor blockade [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
